what is elastic beanstalk?
## **AWS Elastic Beanstalk (Interview-Ready Explanation)**

AWS Elastic Beanstalk is a service used to **deploy and manage applications automatically** in the cloud.
You just upload your code, and Beanstalk handles **servers (EC2), load balancing, scaling, and deployment**.
It supports languages like Java, Node.js, Python, and more.
You don’t need to configure infrastructure manually.
It automatically monitors the application and scales when needed.

---

## 🔥 **Real-Time Example**

👉 “In a Node.js project, instead of manually creating EC2, configuring servers, and deploying code, I upload the code to Elastic Beanstalk, and it automatically deploys and manages everything.”

---

## 💡 **One-Line (Interview Punch)**

👉 “Elastic Beanstalk is used to deploy applications without worrying about infrastructure setup.”

what is CDN?
A CDN (Content Delivery Network) is a distributed network of servers used to deliver content to users faster based on their geographic location.

Instead of serving data from a single server, CDN stores cached copies of content in multiple edge locations worldwide.
This reduces latency and improves website performance.
CDNs are mainly used for images, videos, CSS, JavaScript files, and streaming content.
They also help in handling high traffic and provide better availability.
In AWS, Amazon Web Services provides CDN service called CloudFront.

**Example:**
If a website server is hosted in the US and a user opens it from India, the CDN delivers cached content from the nearest Indian edge location, making the website load much faster.


